<section id="philosophy">
    <h2>Medicine 3.0</h2>

    <div class="key-point">
        <h3>Core Philosophy</h3>
        <blockquote>
            "Medicine 2.0 waits for disease and then treats it. Medicine 3.0 seeks to prevent disease decades before it manifests. We need to shift from reactive sick care to proactive health optimization."
        </blockquote>
    </div>

    <h3>The Four Horsemen</h3>
    <p>Dr. Attia focuses on preventing the four diseases that kill most people in the developed world:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Cardiovascular disease</strong> - Heart attacks, strokes, heart failure</li>
        <li><strong>Cancer</strong> - All types</li>
        <li><strong>Neurodegenerative disease</strong> - Alzheimer's, Parkinson's</li>
        <li><strong>Metabolic disease</strong> - Type 2 diabetes, NAFLD, obesity</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Five Pillars of Longevity</h3>
    <p>His framework for healthspan optimization:</p>
    <ol>
        <li><strong>Exercise</strong> - Both cardiorespiratory fitness and strength</li>
        <li><strong>Nutrition</strong> - Individualized approach, not dogmatic</li>
        <li><strong>Sleep</strong> - Foundation of all other interventions</li>
        <li><strong>Emotional health</strong> - Often neglected but critical</li>
        <li><strong>Medications/supplements</strong> - When indicated based on biomarkers</li>
    </ol>
</section>

<section id="cardiovascular">
    <h2>Cardiovascular Framework</h2>

    <p>Dr. Attia brings deep nuance to cardiovascular risk assessment:</p>

    <h3>ApoB as Primary Marker</h3>
    <div class="key-point">
        <blockquote>
            "ApoB is the best predictor of cardiovascular risk we have. It represents the total number of atherogenic particles in your blood. LDL-C is a surrogate that often misleads."
        </blockquote>
    </div>

    <h3>Key Cardiovascular Concepts</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>ApoB over LDL-C:</strong> Particle number matters more than cholesterol content</li>
        <li><strong>Lp(a):</strong> Genetic risk factor that should be measured in everyone at least once</li>
        <li><strong>Context matters:</strong> Lipid numbers mean different things in metabolic health vs. dysfunction</li>
        <li><strong>Early intervention:</strong> Lower apoB earlier has greater cumulative benefit</li>
        <li><strong>Coronary calcium scoring:</strong> Useful for risk stratification in intermediate-risk patients</li>
    </ul>

